---
import MarketingLayout from '../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro';
---

<MarketingLayout
	title="The Mog Manifesto"
	description="A sharper editorial page for the Mog project: strict defaults, compact syntax, and a runtime that takes itself seriously."
	path="/manifesto/"
>
	<section class="content-section manifesto-shell">
		<div class="section-header">
			<span class="eyebrow">Manifesto</span>
			<h1>Mog does not want to be permissive. It wants to be clear.</h1>
			<p>
				This page is the editorial companion to the official docs. The docs explain what Mog does.
				The manifesto explains why the language is being shaped this way in the first place.
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="manifesto-grid">
			<article class="manifesto-card">
				<h3>Strict by default</h3>
				<p>
					Mog treats explicitness as a feature, not a tax. Function signatures, package APIs, and
					type checking are part of the language’s posture, not optional afterthoughts.
				</p>
			</article>
			<article class="manifesto-card">
				<h3>Compact without becoming vague</h3>
				<p>
					The syntax tries to stay clean while still drawing hard boundaries. Semicolons are not
					normal statement punctuation. Newline continuation is explicit. The parser is not asked
					to guess your intent.
				</p>
			</article>
			<article class="manifesto-card">
				<h3>Runtime seriousness</h3>
				<p>
					The project already includes a compiler, a bytecode VM, native package loading, stack
					traces, and frontend timing diagnostics. Mog is not trying to look like a language. It is
					trying to behave like one.
				</p>
			</article>
			<article class="manifesto-card">
				<h3>One repo, one toolchain story</h3>
				<p>
					The language, examples, packages, tests, editor support, and now the official docs all
					live together. That keeps the public site close to the real implementation instead of
					drifting into marketing fiction.
				</p>
			</article>
		</div>

		<div class="manifesto-cta">
			<div>
				<span class="eyebrow">Continue</span>
				<h2>The argument is one thing. The docs are the proof.</h2>
				<p>Use the official docs for build instructions, language basics, tooling, packages, and reference material.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="hero-actions">
				<a class="primary" href="/docs/">Open the Docs</a>
				<a class="secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/install/">Install and Build</a>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>
</MarketingLayout>
